  "doc_id": "9045",
  "text": "Because of limited metabolic capacity of the neonate, it was hypothesized that GIN would not be efficiently hydrolyzed to GEN [CITATION_1] ) and, further, that phase II metabolism such as glucuronidation would also be limited [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Few studies have reported exposing neo natal rodents orally to GIN because of their small size; however, in a pilot study we demon strated that oral GIN elicited estrogenic activity . Neonatal mice treated orally on days 2-5 with 25 mg/kg GIN showed increased uterine wet weight gain similar to mice that received 20 mg/kg GEN sc, thus indicating that approximately 80% of orally administered GIN reached sufficient circulating levels of the active compound to elicit a biological effect compared with sc GEN ). This is important because [CITATION_5] argued that orally administered GIN, the form available to infants consuming soy formula, was not biologically active as an estrogen and therefore could not cause adverse effects associated with other environmental estrogens.",
